12:24.607 --> 12:25.989
And here are your hosts.

12:30.876 --> 12:32.859
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane.

12:33.159 --> 12:37.005
The award-winning novel Ringworld is probably Larry Niven's finest work.

12:37.025 --> 12:43.734
The Ringworld is an immense ring, large enough to hold three million Earths, and with a thousand-mile high wall to hold in its atmosphere.

12:44.275 --> 12:45.837
It also has continents and oceans.

12:46.378 --> 12:51.846
The Ringworld contains trillions of inhabitants of different species and derives energy from the sun at its center.

12:52.231 --> 12:56.717
Niven recalls where he obtained the idea for such a fantastic structure.

12:56.737 --> 13:00.381
I ran across the concept Dyson sphere.

13:01.603 --> 13:12.937
Dyson, the mathematician, came up with the concept Dyson shell, and he was misunderstood to some extent, so presently I ran across an article about Dyson spheres.

13:13.378 --> 13:21.208
Picture that as a golf ball 93 million miles in radius with a sun at the center, and

13:21.610 --> 13:39.568
gravity generators all around the outside so you would live on the inside terraform it with oceans and soil and air I ran across that and I didn't like it I thought it could be improved and I wound up with the Ringworld

13:47.041 --> 13:52.808
Readers studied the science behind the Ringworld and wrote Niven about seeming inconsistencies in the design of the immense artifact.

13:53.970 --> 13:59.417
Call them errors and elaborations because some of them don't really fit the error thing.

13:59.537 --> 14:02.641
It's just something that hadn't gotten into the original book.

14:03.682 --> 14:06.085
One of the errors was spotted by some MIT students.

14:06.486 --> 14:08.468
It had to do with the instability of the Ringworld.

14:09.469 --> 14:13.795
I suspected the Ringworld was unstable, and I suspected you'd eat at it, Jed.

14:14.516 --> 14:14.736
I...

14:15.087 --> 14:24.101
was sure that the Ringworld was spinning fast enough to permit bizarre dramjets to be used as attitude jets, which means you don't have a fuel problem at all.

14:24.121 --> 14:25.403
You're burning the solar wind.

14:26.545 --> 14:36.281
But rapidly, some MIT people demonstrated that the Ringworld was unstable, and they were chanting it in the halls at the next world gone.

14:36.441 --> 14:37.963
The Ringworld is unstable.

14:38.144 --> 14:42.090
The Ringworld is unstable.

14:42.695 --> 14:48.665
It still took about seven years for anyone to figure out the exact numbers for the instability.

14:48.945 --> 14:50.127
And they are horrifying.

14:50.167 --> 14:59.782
The Ringworld, a major solar flare would have the Ringworld grinding against its sun in five years.

14:59.802 --> 15:01.105
Well, I worked it into the plot.

15:01.766 --> 15:04.670
That was one elaboration or error.

15:05.812 --> 15:09.478
Even teenage readers analyzed his Ringworld with a critical scientific eye.

15:10.302 --> 15:22.309
A high school class in Florida got to work on the Ringworld, and their conclusion was that the Ringworld's worst problem is that all the topsoil would wind up in the oceans in about 3,000 years.

15:23.111 --> 15:27.501
There are no earthquakes on the Ringworld, no mountain-building forces.

15:35.227 --> 15:40.514
But in a sequel, Ringworld Engineers, Niven attempted to correct such deficiencies.

15:40.534 --> 15:44.839
He devised a way to answer the criticism of the Florida high schoolers.

15:44.859 --> 15:47.442
Okay, that's a tough one.

15:47.523 --> 15:58.456
I set up a spill pipe system that runs the top, that runs the sea bottom muck from the sea bottoms under the Ringworld and up over the edge of the rim wall.

16:00.599 --> 16:02.922
That even allows you some...

16:04.218 --> 16:10.045
some mind's accumulation of useful metals.

16:20.759 --> 16:31.052
Fan response of that sort caused Ringworld engineers to be written, and although Niven once said he wouldn't write anymore in the known space series, the body of stories to which Ringworld belongs, he's not so sure anymore.

16:32.433 --> 16:37.743
I've given up saying that the known space series is dead.

16:38.605 --> 16:39.887
There's just no point in it.

16:39.967 --> 16:44.556
I've written five books worth of known space stories since I said that.

16:45.238 --> 16:53.293
More on Larry Niven tomorrow.

